<p><strong><span style=3D"color: #ff00ff;">General Baking Vessel Substituti=
on Rules:</span> <em><span style=3D"color: #ff00ff;">When baking in a pan o=
ther than what is called for in a recipe, the baking time (not the temperat=
ure) will need to be increased or decreased based on the volume of the batt=
er, in relation to the width and depth of the pans.</span></em></strong></p=
>
<p>For example, let=E2=80=99s say I follow a recipe for an <a href=3D"http:=
//comfortablydomestic.com/2013/01/06/new-year-new-you/">8-inch round layer =
cake</a>.&nbsp;Once the batter is made, I realize that my boys have abscond=
ed with my 8-inch round pans. Since the volume of batter remains unchanged =
regardless of the size of the pans that I bake it in, I may instead bake th=
e batter in two 9 x 4-inch loaf pans. &nbsp;Easy stuff, eh? However, the ba=
king time needs to be extended because the 9 x 4-inch loaf pans have a smal=
ler surface area and a greater depth than the 8-inch round pans.</p>
<p>Wait. <em>What?</em></p>
<p>You see, the aforementioned loaf pans are taller and not as wide as the =
round pans for which they&nbsp;are&nbsp;being substituted for&nbsp;in the r=
ecipe. Our <a href=3D"http://comfortablydomestic.com/2012/02/03/food-dork-f=
ridays-heat/">FDF discussion on heat</a> told us that convection currents c=
ause batters bake from the outside in; so the batter, being denser in the t=
aller pan, will take longer to bake than would batter in a shallower pan.</=
p>
<p>The opposite is true when using a larger or shallower pan than directed =
by a recipe. If I were to follow a recipe calling for a 9 x 13-inch pan, bu=
t instead I decided to <a href=3D"http://comfortablydomestic.com/2010/05/11=
/yankee-sheet-cake/">bake the batter in a half sheet pan</a>, the half-shee=
t pan will bake the batter in less time than required by the 9 x 13-inch, b=
ecause the half-sheet pan is both more shallow and has a greater surface ar=
ea than the 9 x 13-inch pan.&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://comfortablydomestic.com=
/2013/02/10/red-velvet-vanilla-marble-cupcakes/">Cupcakes</a> will bake eve=
n faster for the same reasons.</p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: #ff00ff;">A Word of Caution:</span></stron=
g> While I=E2=80=99ve outlined volume equivalents for various baking pans, =
do not forget&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://comfortablydomestic.com/2013/01/25/foo=
d-dork-fridays-leavening-2/">the important roll that leavening plays</a> in=
 the grand scheme of things. Extended baking times for deeper pans may mean=
 that the leavening exhausts itself before the batter has finished baking=
=E2=80=93this can result in a cake that is beautiful around the edges with =
a sunken middle. Such an&nbsp;occurrence,&nbsp;while tragic, <a href=3D"htt=
p://comfortablydomestic.com/2010/08/17/t-isnt-always-rosy/">can sometimes b=
e salvaged with a little creativity</a>&nbsp;on the fly.</p>
<p><strong>As a courtesy to my international readers, I=E2=80=99ve included=
 a second baking pan conversion chart,&nbsp;with American to Metric pan con=
versions.</strong></p>
