days-baking-pan-conversion-chart/#comment-18048">April 25, 2017 at 5:29 pm<=
/a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class=3D"comment-content">
		=09
			I'm not trying to be rude, but this is not the correct way to scale a ca=
ke recipe to a different size cake pan.  Knowing the pan capacity doesn't t=
ell you anything other than pan capacity.  An 8" pan holds 4 cups of batter=
.  You want to make two 10" round cakes.  According to the chart, 22 cups o=
f batter will be required.

So, how much more baking soda?  How much more butter?  How much more flour?=
 =20

If baking by volume, you would need more than five times the batter if goin=
g from a 8" to two 10" inch round cakes.

But if you double, triple, quadruple the recipe, you totally skew the ratio=
s.  Successful baking is about keeping ingredients in the correct ratios.  =
Throw the eggs and leavening off, and the cakes will fail.  Throw the sugar=
 to fats off, and the cakes will fail.

Knowing two 10" rounds hold 22 cups of batter doesn't tell you how much of =
each ingredient you actually need.

The first step is use weight, not volume when baking.

To scale a cake recipe, you have to do the following:=20
1. Calculate the area of the pan called for in the recipe
2. Calculate the area of the pan you would like to use
3. Calculate the difference in area in percentages between the two pans.
4. Calculate the baker's percentages of the recipe ingredients=20
5. Calculate the baker's percentages of increased amounts of ingredients ba=
sed on the difference in area between the two pans

For example. You have a recipe for a 8" round and you want to bake a 9" rou=
nd.
1. Square the radius
2. Multiply the the radius squared by pi (3.14)

Radius of 8 is 4
4 x 4 =3D 16
16 x 3.14 =3D 50.24. (round down)

The area of the 8" round is approximately 50"

Radius of 9 is 4.5
4.5 x 4.5 =3D 20.25
20.25 x 3.14 =3D 63 58 (round up)

The area of the 9" round is approximately 64"

Divide the larger pan area into the smaller pan area:

64 / 50 =3D 1.28

For a 9" cake, the recipes needs to be increased by 28%.

From there, use baker's percentages to calculate 28% more of each ingredien=
t.		</div>

